<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Wine Body to Salmon Preparation Method</strong> - Wild salmon's leaner texture pairs beautifully with medium-bodied wines like Burgundian Chardonnay or Loire Valley Sancerre, while rich farmed salmon can handle fuller wines like oaked Chardonnay or even light Pinot Noir. The key is matching the wine's weight to the fish's fat content—lean preparations need crisp acidity to cleanse the palate, while buttery or cedar-plank preparations can support more substantial wines.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve White Wines at 50-55°F for Optimal Salmon Pairing</strong> - This temperature range is slightly warmer than typical white wine service but crucial for salmon pairings. At 50-55°F, the wine's acidity remains bright enough to cut through the fish's oils while allowing subtle flavor compounds like the mineral notes in Chablis or the citrus oils in Riesling to complement salmon's delicate flavor without overwhelming it.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Wines with Natural Acidity Over High-Alcohol Options</strong> - Salmon's natural oils require wines with tartaric acid levels above 6 grams per liter to provide proper palate cleansing. German Riesling, Muscadet, or unoaked Sauvignon Blanc excel here, while high-alcohol wines (above 14%) can create an unpleasant metallic taste when combined with salmon's omega-3 fatty acids.</li>

  <li><strong>Skip Decanting for Most Salmon-Friendly Wines</strong> - The delicate, fresh character that makes wines perfect for salmon—crisp minerality, bright acidity, subtle fruit—can be diminished by aggressive aeration. Only decant if serving an older Burgundian Pinot Noir with grilled salmon, and even then, limit exposure to 15-20 minutes to preserve the wine's elegant, food-friendly qualities.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Burgundy or Universal Glasses for Versatility</strong> - Since salmon pairs with both whites and light reds, choose glasses with a moderate bowl size that concentrates aromatics without being too narrow. The shape should direct both the crisp minerality of whites like Sancerre and the earthy notes of Pinot Noir toward your palate, enhancing the complementary relationship between wine and fish.</li>

  <li><strong>Consider Skin-Contact Wines for Grilled or Smoked Salmon</strong> - Orange wines or skin-contact Pinot Grigio provide the perfect bridge between white wine freshness and red wine structure. The subtle tannins from grape skin contact complement the char flavors on grilled salmon while maintaining enough acidity to handle the fish's richness—particularly effective with sockeye or king salmon varieties.</li>

  <li><strong>Drink Young for Most Pairings, but Age Burgundy for Special Occasions</strong> - Most salmon-friendly wines (Sauvignon Blanc, Muscadet, young Chardonnay) should be consumed within 2-3 years to maintain their vibrant acidity. However, if pairing with wild Pacific salmon, consider a 5-7 year old Burgundian Pinot Noir—the wine's developed earthiness beautifully mirrors the fish's complex, mineral-driven flavors from cold Pacific waters.</li>

  <li><strong>Time Your Wine Service to Salmon's Temperature</strong> - Serve wine slightly before the salmon reaches the table. Cold salmon (in salads or sashimi preparations) pairs best with wines at cellar temperature, while hot preparations benefit from wine that's had 5-10 minutes to warm slightly. This temperature harmony prevents the thermal shock that can make both the wine and fish taste flat or overly aggressive.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing wine with grilled salmon versus poached salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Grilled salmon develops char and caramelized flavors that can handle bolder wines like Côtes du Rhône or medium-bodied Cabernet Sauvignon, while poached salmon's delicate preparation pairs beautifully with lighter options like Sancerre or unoaked Chardonnay. The cooking method dramatically affects the salmon's flavor intensity—grilled fish creates smoky, concentrated flavors that complement wines with more tannins and body. Poached salmon retains its natural sweetness and flaky texture, making it ideal for crisp, mineral-driven whites that won't overpower the fish.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve wine with salmon chilled or at room temperature?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">White wines should be served well-chilled at 45-50°F to enhance their acidity and complement salmon's rich oils, while light reds like Pinot Noir benefit from slight chilling to 55-60°F. Room temperature reds can overwhelm delicate salmon preparations, so even medium-bodied options like Grenache should be served slightly cooler than typical red wine service temperature. The key is balancing the wine's temperature with salmon's natural richness—cooler wines provide refreshing contrast to the fish's fatty acids.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is wine with salmon good for beginners who don't usually drink wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely—salmon's rich, mild flavor profile makes it one of the most forgiving foods for wine pairing, especially for newcomers. Start with approachable options like Riesling, Sauvignon Blanc, or light Pinot Noir, which complement without competing with the fish's natural flavors. The omega-3 oils in salmon actually soften wine tannins and acidity, making even dry wines taste smoother and more balanced. This creates an ideal learning experience where both the wine and food enhance each other without overwhelming an inexperienced palate.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when choosing wine for salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is ignoring the sauce or seasoning and focusing only on the fish itself—a lemon-herb salmon needs different wine than teriyaki-glazed salmon. Many people also default to "white wine with fish" without considering that salmon's richness can handle light reds beautifully. Another frequent mistake is serving wines too warm, which can make them taste unbalanced against salmon's delicate flavors and natural oils.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can you pair red wine with salmon, and which types work best?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, light to medium-bodied red wines pair exceptionally well with salmon, particularly Pinot Noir, Gamay, and Grenache. These wines have sufficient acidity to cut through salmon's richness while offering complementary earthy and fruity notes that enhance the fish's flavor. Avoid heavy, tannic reds like Cabernet Sauvignon or Syrah unless the salmon is heavily seasoned or grilled with bold marinades. The key is choosing reds with bright acidity and moderate tannins that won't overpower the fish's delicate texture.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibel text-wine-700 mb-2">What are good budget-friendly wine alternatives for salmon under $15?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Excellent budget options include Portuguese Vinho Verde for its crisp minerality, Spanish Albariño for its seafood-friendly acidity, and Oregon Pinot Gris for its balanced richness. For reds, look for Loire Valley Chinon or Sancerre Rouge, which offer Pinot Noir's salmon-friendly characteristics at lower prices. Many Washington State and Chilean Sauvignon Blancs under $15 provide the citrusy brightness that complements salmon beautifully while delivering exceptional value.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How does wild versus farmed salmon affect wine pairing choices?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Wild salmon typically has firmer texture, more intense flavor, and less fat content, making it ideal for wines with more structure like Chablis or Loire Valley whites. Farmed salmon tends to be richer and more buttery due to higher fat content, pairing beautifully with creamier wines like oaked Chardonnay or soft Pinot Noir. The difference in oil content means farmed salmon can handle slightly more robust wines, while wild salmon's lean profile benefits from crisp, mineral-driven selections that enhance rather than compete with its natural flavors.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I open wine with salmon immediately before serving or let it breathe?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most white wines paired with salmon should be served immediately after opening to preserve their fresh, crisp character that complements the fish's delicate flavors. Light reds like Pinot Noir can benefit from 15-30 minutes of breathing to soften any residual tannins and allow fruit flavors to emerge. Avoid extended decanting with salmon pairings, as the goal is maintaining the wine's bright acidity and fresh aromatics that provide perfect contrast to the fish's rich oils.</p>
